DKIM2 reflector tests (dkim2.com)
=================================

The dkim2.com reflector replies to a message you send it with a DKIM2-signed
(and sometimes modified) copy, so you can check your verifier against an
independent implementation.  Every test below exercises the **verify** path:
phoenixdkim consumes the reflector's chain.  Emitting recipes as a modifying
intermediary is a separate, still-deferred piece (the in-milter modification
engine) and is not needed for any of these.

Status as of the DKIM2-extended work (recipe library + cross-instance
verification; verification is automatic, no new daemon config):

  Test                          Status   Why
  ----------------------------  -------   -----------------------------------------
  reflector-fresh@dkim2.com     Yes       Originates a minimal message (one MI +
                                          one sig); a plain inbound core chain,
                                          exactly what DKIM2Mode verify checks.
  reflector-raw@dkim2.com       Yes       Re-signs an unchanged message: you
                                          originate-sign outbound, it adds a hop,
                                          you verify the multi-hop chain.  No
                                          modification, so the originator hash
                                          still matches.  Pure core.
  reflector-damage@dkim2.com    Yes       Mutates the body after signing; expected
                                          result is a body-hash FAIL, which the
                                          verifier reports (and rejects under
                                          DKIM2RejectOnFail).
  reflector-brand@dkim2.com     Mostly    ESP brand delegation via DNS CNAME: the
                                          chain is core, the delegation is just key
                                          lookup the live-DNS verify follows.
                                          Doable, but needs the CNAME/key
                                          delegation set up and is the least
                                          exercised path.
  reflector-subject@dkim2.com   Yes       Subject modified + reversible recipe.
                                          The verifier reconstructs the previous
                                          instance from the m=2 recipe and
                                          re-checks the originator's m=1 hashes.
  reflector-body@dkim2.com      Yes       Body footer + reversible recipe; same
                                          backward reconstruction as subject.
  reflector-both@dkim2.com      Yes       Subject + body recipes together.
  reflector-redacted@dkim2.com  Yes       Non-reversible change r={"b":null}: the
                                          parser treats a null part as
                                          irreversible, so the chain passes up to
                                          that hop without attempting to
                                          reconstruct it (verify-passes,
                                          reconstruct-not-attempted) -- the
                                          intended result.

Running them
------------

The reflector is driven by email, so you need a path that can send to and
receive from dkim2.com and a phoenixdkim instance verifying inbound DKIM2
(DKIM2Mode=verify or both).  The cross-instance recipe checks run automatically
once a reply carries multiple Message-Instances.  For an offline dry run of the
extended path without the reflector, the phoenixdkim2-sign/-verify CLIs
reproduce subject/body/both with --orig (see docs/dkim2-dev-guide.md, "Verify
end-to-end").
